ian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hvarflad Agatha Gormflarth Haakonsdottir was born in 1090, in Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland. She married GilleBride MacGille Adomnan about 1110, in Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1090–":"1090–Surnud","1080–1164":"1080–1164","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1113–1164":"1113–1164","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1118–Female":"1118–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1116":"1116","about 1118":"umbes 1118","1113":"1113","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","about 1110":"umbes 1110","Orkney, Scotland":"Orkney, Scotland","Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland":"Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Scotland","scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1090–":"1090–Kuollut","1080–1164":"1080–1164","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1113–1164":"1113–1164","1116–Female":"1116–Kuollut","1118–Female":"1118–Kuollut","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1090":"1090","1116":"1116","about 1118":"noin 1118","1113":"1113","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","about 1110":"noin 1110","Orkney, Scotland":"Orkney, Scotland","Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland":"Orkney Islands, Orkney, Scotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Scotland","scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1090–":"1090–Décédée","1080–1164":"1080–1164","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","1113–1164":"1113–1164","1116–Female":"1116–Décédée"